				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\frac{{\rm{\partial }}U}{{\rm{\partial }}z}=i{k}_{r}\frac{{N}_{m}(P)}{{D}_{n}(P)}U$$\end{document}where Nm and Dn are polynomials in the operator P, and (m, n) is the order of approximation. Our numerical capabilities allowed us to make use of the (1, 1) Padé order, corresponding to Nm = P/2 and Dn = 1 + P/4.
